To clarify, this isn't a Greek sorority or fraternity. We are open to all fields in healthcare studies such as medical, dental, pharmaceutical, physical therapy, nursing, occupational therapy, and veterinarian.

 

Membership

Associate Membership
Associate Member Application, 3.0 GPA, pre-health track.

 

National Membership- OPTIONAL 
One time fee of $75, National Member Application, 3.2 Cumulative/Science GPA.

*** Must be an Associate member for at least 1 semester before applying for National

Name: Alpha Phi Alpha Fraternity, Inc.
Description: The History of Alpha Phi Alpha Fraternity Inc. Since it's founding on December 4, 1906, Alpha Phi Alpha Fraternity, Inc. has supplied voice and vision to the struggle of African-Americans and people of color around the world. Alpha Phi Alpha, the first intercollegiate Greek-letter fraternity established for African-Americans, was founded at Cornell University in Ithaca, New York by seven college men who recognized the need for a strong bond of Brotherhood among African descendants in this country. The visionary founders, known as the “Jewels” of the Fraternity, are Henry Arthur Callis, Charles Henry Chapman, Eugene Kinckle Jones, George Biddle Kelley, Nathaniel Allison Murray, Robert Harold Ogle, and Vertner Woodson Tandy. The Fraternity initially served as a study and support group for minority students who faced racial prejudice, both educationally and socially, at Cornell. The Jewel founders and early leaders of the Fraternity suc-ceeded in laying a firm foundation for Alpha Phi Alpha's principles of scholarship, fellowship, good character, and the uplifting of humanity. Alpha Phi Alpha chapters were established at other colleges and universities, many of them historically black institutions, soon after the founding at Cornell. The first Alumni Chapter was established in 1911. While continuing to stress academic excellence among its members, Alpha also recognized the need to help correct the educational, economic, political, and social injustices faced by African-Americans. True to its form as the “first of firsts,” Alpha Phi Alpha has been interracial since 1945.

Name: American Student Dental Association FIU Chapter
Description:
As a pre-dental division, the FIU chapter aspires to create leaders and well rounded dental school applicants. We provide numerous opportunities to get involved in leadership and health-related activities locally and globally, as well as professional development, and skills workshops. We're here for YOU! Don't miss out on  the great opportunities we have to offer.

ASDA purpose is much more than a chapter who guides you into dental school, we are here to provide useful information after you graduate. ASDA will guide you through anything from DAT study tips to entrepreneurship post-graduation information. We can offer DAT prep courses, live chats with dental councilors from several dental schools, free workshops, a book with the current acceptance scores (average DAT scores, average GPA, average science GPA, etc.) to all the dental schools here in the US. Also, a monthly magazine with all the up to date tech, what’s going on around the world in the dental aspect, valuable tips on becoming a professional, how to succeed in the work place, and much more. ASDA will guide you by showing you what it takes to open your own clinic, what it takes to get a job and how to balance those financial struggles. We focus on this heavily because getting the diploma is only half the problem, you need leadership skills, you must be able to interact, and know what’s happening in the world around you.

The American Student Dental Association is a national student-run organization that protects and advances the rights, interests and welfare of pre-dental students. It introduces students to lifelong involvement in organized dentistry and provides services, information, education, representation and advocacy.

When you join ASDA, you’re given a voice – in your education and profession – and a chance to be part of a strong network of future dentists. You’ll also have the opportunity to develop the leadership skills that will benefit you throughout your life.

The Value of Membership goes beyond what you receive in your four years of dental school. Many ASDA members meet life-long friends and professional mentors who make a positive impact on your career.

Only 50% of applicants are accepted into dental school each year. Predental ASDA membership will provide you with the best opportunity to stand apart from your competition and improve your chances of getting into dental school.

As a member, you’ll receive The Guide to Getting Into Dental School. This handbook contains tuition information, undergraduate requirements, application requirements and statistics for all 66 U.S. dental schools. It also provides helpful information on the predental timeline, the DAT, interviewing, choosing a school and more.

In addition, you will also begin receiving ASDA’s monthly e-newsletter, The Polished Predental.

Name: Association of Latino Professionals for America
Description: The Association of Latino Professionals for America (ALPFA) is the largest business student organization at Florida International University, and a leading student chapter of one of the largest professional organizations for Latinos in the nation. ALPFA at FIU continues to build upon this legacy of shared values and guiding principles and as such has earned the ALPFA regional student chapter of the year award a record 11 of the 13 years since the awards establishment as well as 2022 National Student Chapter of the Year and 2023 Southeast Student Chapter of the Year.

Name: Badminton
Description:
Hello and welcome to FIU Badminton Club.

 

We are here to provide a space for members, students, faculty, staff and community members to play and enjoy badminton. We work to support and represent badminton in Miami as one of 4 locations that provide a regular scheduled facilities which provide a space to play.

 

We have 3 courts and a wide variety of skill level of players. Please come and join us. 
Rackets and shuttles are NOT provided by the club (limited number is available for rental at the PRO SHOP) as we DO NOT collect any dues or fees at the current time.

 

HOWEVER, please remember that you are expected provide shuttles to the game that you are currently involved (quality depends on the other members who will be playing with you).
As there are a lot of members in at the courts please remember that we all share the space. Therefore, you should limit yourselves to 2 games to 21 points and switch to allow others to also play their 2 games and continue to rotate in and out according to the queue at each specific court.

 

Additional information such as competitions during the year and coaching is available upon request as well as locations of other facilities.

 

Please join ask to join the WhatsApp Group and read the group descriptions for practice times and any further information will be posted there.

Thank you very much and looking forward to see y'all out there.

 

-Mel

Now also at BBC!

These materials could be for cool projects, useful gadgets, or anything that you want to bring to life. We will be focusing on both the proposal, business, and design processes, as well as the actual construction and manufacturing for each project or item.

There will be organized educational sessions and workshops to give members the skills in preparation for making their designs and proposing their production in the future. These seminars include learning how to use a 3D printer, how to use 3D modeling software such as SolidWorks and Google SketchUp, programming business, and how to design in general.

We accept any FIU student from any major and any background that wants to make great things or learn how to get on the right track to making it, though Honors students will receive special offers. Don’t be afraid to contact us for more information!

Name: Campus Life
Description:
Campus Life provides oversight to student agencies and bureaus (BSU, Homecoming, Panther Power, RSO Council, and SPC), as well as registered  student organizations on campus. 

Campus Life also promotes Hazing Prevention for students involved in any activity on campus. 

Hazing is a violation of the FIU Student Code of Conduct. Hazing is defined as any group or individual action or activity that inflicts or intends to inflict physical or mental harm or discomfort or which may demean, disgrace, or degrade any person, regardless of location, intent, or consent of participant(s). Hazing includes, but is not limited to, forced consumption of any food, alcohol, controlled substances, drugs, or any other substance, forced physical activity, deprivation of food or sleep, physical abuse of any nature, and verbal abuse, including yelling or demands.

For more information about Hazing Prevention, the mandatory student training, or to report a hazing incident, please visit the FIU Hazing Prevention site.

Our offices are located on the MMC Campus in GC2240 and on the BBC Campus in WUC 141.

Name: Campus Life BBC Branch
Description:

Through education and mentoring, Campus Life seeks to provide our students an opportunity to make meaningful connections and become leaders in a global community. The Department of Campus Life provides a variety of programs and services to students and University community. 

Students’ academic learning is enhanced through their active participation in additional educational opportunities in the areas of leadership development, communication and organizational skills, services, event planning, and evaluating techniques. There are many areas in which students may choose to become involved, including: Student Government Association, Panther Power, Student Programming Council, Student Organization Council, Black Student Association, Homecoming and Bayview Hall Council. 

Professional staff members are also available to assists students in pursuing their interests. And remember, we are here to help make your FIU experience as eventful as possible, as you live THE BAY LIFE!

Name: Center for Academic Success
Description:
The Center for Academic Success (CfAS) is housed under Academic and Career Success (ACS). Located at both MMC and BBC, the center facilitates the academic advancement of students by providing support in an environment that is conducive to teaching and learning.

Students can access tutoring in a variety of subject areas, as well as participate in programs that develop their critical thinking and learning strategies. With a comprehensive approach, services are delivered in person or online via one-on-one sessions, small groups, study halls, or workshops.

CfAS interacts with undergraduate students at all levels throughout their academic experience; from preparing students before admission to assisting them along the pathway towards graduation. The center fosters constructive relationships between students and tutors, and incorporates high and low-tech tools to enhance learning, improve retention, and promote academic excellence.

Name: Center for Excellence in Writing

Our multilingual staff is dedicated to creating a welcoming, respectful, and collaborative environment to help all writers succeed in the classroom and in their communities.

Name: Center for Leadership
Description:
About Us

Ethical and effective leadership is defined by the quality of the choices leaders make for themselves, their organizations and the communities they serve. The Center for Leadership at Florida International University understands that for leaders to position themselves to make better decisions more often, the process of leadership development should be continuous and intentional. Over time, what also should develop is a personal leadership philosophy, a deeper understanding of self and a repertoire of competencies consistent with effective leadership outcomes.

Effective leadership is evidenced and defined by behavior and action – it’s not about “being” a leader, but “doing leadership well.” The Center’s model for leadership development, then, focuses on two epicenters: self-insight and developable skills.

  • Self-Insight: To be most effective a leader must first begin to look inward and be prepared to take a deep dive into who they are, how they think, how they view the world, and to question the basis for these perceptions. While it is unlikely that an individual may be able to change these more core characteristics, deep self-awareness can help leaders proactively manage leadership behaviors.
  • Leadership skills: The application of cutting-edge research vetted by leading practitioners allows leaders to learn, practice and develop actionable skills and behaviors consistent with effective leadership.

The Center for Leadership faculty and staff are dedicated to exploring leadership thought and practice through continuous research, providing opportunities for leaders to develop keen self-insight, and teaching leadership competencies that will equip them to meaningfully transform their organizations and their societies. Through research, executive development programs and community engagement opportunities, the Center for Leadership is committed to equipping better leaders for a better world.

Our Mission

To provide leadership development that transforms and emboldens individuals and organizations to positively impact our world.

We achieve this by creating new knowledge, presenting innovative developmental paradigms and encouraging leadership conversations across age, industry and levels of responsibility.

Our Vision

To be a unique resource of leadership research and development contributing to an increase of transformational leaders.

Our Impact 

The Center for Leadership at Florida International University is dedicated to exploring leadership thought and practice. Read our reports and learn how we helped build Better Leaders for a Better World.

Name: Center for Leadership and Service
Description: The mission of FIU’s Center for Leadership and Service is to provide students with developmental and experiential opportunities that foster leadership, action, and community engagement. Through leadership education, service, and social innovation, students will become active citizens on-campus, in their respective communities, and globally.

Name: Center for Leadership and Service (CLS) Programs
Description: The mission of the Center for Leadership and Service is to provide students with developmental and experiential opportunities that foster leadership, action, and community engagement. Through leadership education, service, and social innovation, students will become active global citizens on campus, in their respective communities and in the workplace.

Name: Center for Student Engagement
Description:
Explore! Engage! Excel!

The Center for Student Engagement supports student success by fostering academic, career and campus engagement opportunities via collaborative partnerships with the FIU community.  In other words, we’re all about helping YOU be successful at FIU! From workshops and panels to fairs and peer mentors our department provides students with opportunities to thrive.

Name: Central Asian Student Association
Description: This organization serves as a platform for establishing and maintaining the Central Asian Community. It also celebrates and familiarizes FIU students with Central Asian Culture through social events.

Name: Chabad FIU
Description:
Chabad serving Florida International University is part of the Chabad on Campus International network. Our mission is to engage and inspire, encouraging students to be active in their community and contribute to a vibrant, healthy identity that ensures Jewish continuity. Chabad anticipates and serves the needs of its participants on a social, educational, and spiritual level.

Chabad sponsored social events will foster a sense of community and create an opportunity to meet new people. Bursting with life, meaning, and delicious food, holidays at Chabad are an incredible experience designed to help students celebrate Jewish traditions in a fun and accessible way. Chabad also offers Torah study on various topics through classes and one on one sessions. At Chabad, all are welcome, regardless of background, affiliation, and level of observance.

Name: Chemical Society at FIU
Description: The FIU Chemistry Club is a student-run organization, affiliated with the American Chemical Society, that strives to promote public awareness and stimulate interest in chemistry along with other sciences. We use chemistry demonstrations and community involvement to reach out to students of all ages.

Name: Chess Club
Description: The Chess Club @ FIU aims to promote the beautiful, 1500-year-old game of chess to the university. We have meetings for casual play as well as competing in tournaments as a team!

Name: Chi Alpha
Description:
We're not a group of Christians, we're a family of disciples!

Spring '19 Recap Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ju3C23L0voQ&t=12s

 

GATHERINGS

Microchurches:

We unite in Microchurches, gatherings of 5-20 students that meet weekly on campus. Microchurches serve as an ongoing discipleship setting where we worship God together, dialogue through scriptures, overcome personal obstacles and build each other up. Meeting info below:

Monday - 7:00 - Green Library 137

- Contact Elise (954-303-608) for more information

 

@chialpha_fiu - Follow us on Instagram to stay updated and in the loop!

 

ABOUT

Chi Alpha seeks to introduce fellow collegians to an authentic relationship with Jesus Christ. Chi Alpha plans to do this through:

  1. Worship - Expressions of thanks through word, music, and service.
  2. Mission - Living a life that reflects our relationship with God in what we say and do.
  3. Community - Community isn’t something you find by looking for it, it’s the result of looking for God and experiencing mission with other people.

Name: Children's Creative Learning Center
Description: The Center is a self supported university auxiliary and a department within Student Affairs. In addition, the Children’s Center often serves as a demonstration site for departments of the university and programs in the community, e.g.: observation, presentations, special programs, training, and research.

Name: Christian Medical and Dental Association
Description: N/A

Name: Circle K International
Description:
Circle K International is the world's largest student-led community service organization, with thousands of members on hundreds of campuses on five continents across the globe.


The collegiate branch of the Kiwanis International family, CKI is committed to developing leaders by offering unique service, leadership and fellowship opportunities that not only change the world but change members' lives.

 

Service Leadership Program by Kiwanis of Kendall-South Dade. Membership is open to all FIU Students. Sponsored by RSOC.

Name: CL Test Portal
Description: N/A

Name: Clinical Understudy and Research Education
Description: Mission/Purpose: The purpose of this organization shall be to offer advancement in clinically-relevant education, research, and skills for pre-health students, and to better prepare our members to succeed in professional atmospheres while demonstrating the importance of serving our community in and outside the realms of healthcare.

Name: CLS Advanced Leadership Challenge (ALC)
Description: Formerly known as the FIU Advanced Leadership Challenge (ALC), the Certified Student Leader Program is a collaboration within the Division of Student Affairs to provide students with an integrated opportunity to learn, practice, and document their knowledge and ability of the 8 Student Leadership Competencies, which serve as a foundation for effective performance in campus, community, and career roles. Students who successfully complete the program requirements will receive a certificate and the Leadership Medallion. The Certified Student Leader Program is open to Graduate and Undergraduate students enrolled at FIU. There are separate Graduate and Undergraduate tracks. The Certified Student Leader Program is an opportunity for you to be officially recognized for your leadership skills and experiences.

Name: Club for Roleplaying, Imagination and Tabletops
Description:
Welcome to CRIT - the Club for Roleplaying, Imagination, and Tabletops, where reality takes a backseat to the extraordinary! Immerse yourself in a realm where epic adventures unfold with every roll of the dice and where creativity knows no bounds.

Picture this: a gathering of minds, fueled by the sparks of imagination, weaving tales of heroes and villains, exploring uncharted lands, and overcoming challenges that defy the ordinary. At CRIT, we don't just play games; we craft experiences that linger in the mind long after the dice have settled.

Whether you're a seasoned dungeon delver or a newcomer to the world of tabletop gaming, our club is a haven for all who crave a blend of strategy, storytelling, and camaraderie. Dive into the realms of Dungeons & Dragons, discover the intrigue of board games, or let your imagination run wild in collaborative storytelling sessions.

But CRIT is more than just a club; it's a community. Forge bonds with like-minded adventurers, share laughter over epic victories and defeats, and unlock the door to a realm where friendships are forged through shared narratives.

Join CRIT, where every session is a new chapter, every roll of the dice is a twist in the tale, and where your imagination is the only limit. Adventure awaits; are you ready to roll the dice?

Name: Club for Undergraduate Economics Students at FIU
Description: N/A

Name: College Life Coaching Program
Description: College Life Coaching is an initiative that offers undergraduate students valuable one-on-one personal support to achieve not only their academic, but also their personal goals. Students are usually referred to a Life Coach by faculty or staff member, but a student may request an appointment themselves as well.

Name: College of Arts, Sciences & Education
Description:
Our experts work across disciplines and with communities to address the challenges and needs we face as a society. We're leading in groundbreaking and life-changing scientific research, earning teacher-of-the-year honors, penning award-winning works, and developing new products and medicines.

Together, we’re preparing the next generation of creators, explorers and problem solvers to build a future that sustains us all.

Name: College Panhellenic Council
Description: Governing council of the member organizations of the National Panhellenic Conference at FIU.

Name: Common Reading Program
Description:
The Common Reading Program affords students the opportunity of participating in a common curricular experience that creates community and a common ground for discussion.

The program is tailored specifically for incoming first-year students. Students are expected to have read the book before the first day of class and will join together with faculty and peers to discuss and think critically about key concepts. The Common Reading Program will encourage students to partake in intellectual engagement and will create a sense of community among newly admitted Panthers.

Name: Common Sense Action
Description:
Common Sense Action is the first bipartisan advocacy organization of Millennials. Our mission is to disrupt the status quo by bringing Millennial voices to the policy-making table.

CSA serves students from all political backgrounds - Democrats, Republicans, independents, and everywhere in between.  We are different from other groups in that we are a bipartisan - not non-partisan - organization that unites students from across the political spectrum.
CSA chapters host events and discussions, register, remind, and educate voters, and engage with local decision-makers to promote Millennial policy solutions.

Name: Counseling & Psychological Services
Description: Counseling and Psychological Services’ mission is to provide short-term mental health services to students that will facilitate and enhance their personal learning, emotional well-being and academic skills development. CAPS is committed to providing consultation to the FIU community affected by threatened or actual violence and promoting the ability to live a full, rich life.

Name: Creative + Media (Student Life and Development)
Description: N/A

Name: CRO - OrgSync Test
Description: N/A

Name: Cru
Description:
Looking for a community to get plugged into ?

Cru is a community passionate about connecting people to Jesus Christ. No matter where you are in your faith journey, you are welcome here. 

 

We want to be able to build and equip others in the faith to be sent wherever God calls them to be! 

We do all of this through life groups (bible study), action groups (discipleship), evangelism, retreats/conferences, and mission trips.

 

For other ways to get involved, check out our Linktree. 

For more information about Cru in South Florida, click here.

If you're interested to learn more about mission trips, click here.

Name: Cuban American Association of Civil Engineers
Description:
Founded in Miami in 1961, membership originally was open only to Civil Engineers that had formerly exercised their profession in Cuba, and who agreed with the goals of the Association.

Today, our association maintains over 400 members and associates and any Civil Engineer is welcome to join no matter the nationality.

FIU has the only student chapter of CAACE which means we have all the opportunities to network and get to be known in the professional world. We are not limited to Cuban-Americans only. We encourage and welcome any Civil Engineering student who wants to join no matter his/her nationality. In order to be a members an e-board officer has to invite you to join; so if you wish to be part of our association and you have not been yet invited, please contact us with the subject “Request to Join” so we could send you an invitation. E‐board officer terms are yearly‐based, and this term will be from Fall 2013 to Spring 2014.

Name: Cuban Heritage Society
Description: Cuban Heritage Society is an organization created with the purpose of celebrating, promoting, and protecting Cuban heritage and culture. Our goal is to raise awareness about the human rights violations in Cuba, while providing all FIU students with cultural and philanthropic events that engage and educate.

Name: Delta Epsilon Mu
Description: Delta Epsilon Mu is the only professional pre-health fraternity in the nation. Our organization works with pre-health students across medicine, dentistry, nursing, psychology, and veterinary studies. As a unique asset to prestigious universities across the United States, we strive to employ our principles of dedication, loyalty, friendship, and support in all of our efforts. From educational programs to fundraising, to community service, members of Delta Epsilon Mu participate in a diverse set of activities. Our network is comprised of individuals of all backgrounds to produce a strong network of well-rounded doctors, students, pharmacists, veterinarians, etc. This national organization provides students and the community with a non-judgmental, inclusive resource for uniting professional across the health fields and "helping people together".

Name: Delta Sigma Phi
Description: Founded in 1899 in the City College of New York, Delta Sigma Phi was created on the principles of diversity and good character. The mission of Delta Sigma Phi is to create better men to lead a better life. This atypical fraternity continues to link men of all backgrounds through a unity of brotherhood to spark a social movement.

Name: Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc.
Description: The “Illustrious” Iota Pi chapter of Delta Sigma Theta Sorority Inc. was chartered at Florida International University.

Name: Delta Tau Delta
Description: Delta Tau Delta is rich in history. Founded in 1858 in what is now West Virginia, Delta Tau Delta has stood the test of time. It has survived two world wars, a Great Depression and a great recession, the boom of undergraduates brought on by the G.I. Bill, and the reduction of Fraternity membership following the Vietnam War. If you decide to join Delta Tau Delta, you can feel comfort in knowing that more than 150 years of history and tradition will be there to greet you.

Name: Department of Marketing & Logistics
Description: N/A

Name: Dept of History GSO (DOHGSA)
Description: The purpose of DOHGSA is to complement academic programs of study by enhancing the overall educational experience of students through the development of, exposure to, and participation in academic, cultural, professional, service, social & recreational activities, among others.

Name: Dermatology Interest Group
Description: N/A

Name: Diagnostic/Interventional Radiology Interest Group
Description: N/A

Name: Disability Resource Center
Description:
As your partners in success, we are committed to you. Serving as the one-stop-shop for your disability service needs, the DRC provides the resources to facilitate a smooth transition to university life. By providing one-on-one consultation throughout your academic journey at FIU, our DRC staff is a specialized resource for you.

The DRC website is just one of the many resources available so that students with disabilities can access all that FIU has to offer throughout our diverse academic community.

Name: Disabled Student Union
Description: The Disabled Student Union (DSU) is established to provide a safe, accessible, and inclusive space for all students. The DSU aims to empower students by advocating for Disability justice, educating others about barriers of inaccessibility on campus, building relationships with administration, establishing a strong FIU community through impactful intersectional programming, and creating connections in South Florida, and the greater community for Disabled people.

Name: Discipline-Based Education Research (DBER) Alliance
Description:
Discipline-Based Education Research (DBER) is the collective methods, theories, and models that examine teaching and learning within science disciplines. The Discipline-Based Education Research Alliance (DBER-A) is an inclusive term used to emphasize the interdisciplinary nature of this DBER and calls for an alliance of the disciplines to exchange resources and act as supportive structures for DBER students and researchers (Henderson, 2017). This alliance also serves as a community of practice for DBER researchers. "Communities of practice are groups of people who share a concern or a passion for something they do and learn how to do it better as they interact regularly" (Wenger-Trayner, 2015). We do not expect that there may be challenges (Talanquer, 2014) but are optimistic that combining resources and expertise will be of great value to FIU's DBER students. The DBER student organization aims to address concerns faced by all DBER students, regardless of the discipline. These challenges include but are not limited to the following:
Institutional and Departmental Support for DBER Students: DBER is Interdisciplinary, with Variability Across DBER Programs and professional challenges for DBER Students. This organization is not meant to diminish the intricacies between the disciplines but to supplement and complement their students' and researchers' shared resources and experiences and is open to all education researchers at FIU.

The DBER student organization envisions creating an environment where students have the capital and agency to advocate for their needs, advance and progress academically and professionally, and succeed in their DBER program of study. The DBER student organization will instill students with academic resources to progress in their DBER program through collaboration, community building, resource sharing and exchange, and developing a repository of academic and professional resources for DBER students.
The goal of DBER-A is to strengthen, maintain, and sustain FIU’s DBER programs of study across disciplines, provide academic, research, and professional resources to DBER students, and provide opportunities for community building, mentorship, network building, and interdisciplinary collaboration.

While BER, CER, EER, and PER comprise most of the DBER work at FIU, research interests, scope, and methodology vary. DBER students and labs study populations along the K-20 continuum in formal and informal settings. Research scope may include teaching and learning at levels of analysis that include research, policy, and practice. DBER students have studied science literacy, student reflective practices, mentorship models, and student affect, such as motivation, identity, agency, capital, resilience, sense-making, and sense of belonging. At this time, Florida International University does not have an astronomy or geoscience education research lab, but we welcome the participation of students interested in AER.

Name: Division of Academic and Student Affairs
Description:
The Division of Academic & Student Affairs at FIU is devoted to providing high-quality education opportunities and effective academic and student support services to optimize learner success. With nearly 50 departments, the division is committed to responding to the changing landscape of higher education and preparing students for the rigors of the 21st-century workplace, while providing a meaningful learning experience for students in and outside the classroom.

The division supports a well-rounded, workforce-ready student and fosters an enduring connection to the university by teaching civic responsibility, leadership, and commitment to service; nurturing an understanding of diversity; contributing to academic success by providing support services and experiential learning opportunities; and providing professional development and career recruitment opportunities. Our university community has a tradition of excellence, and you are part of this unforgettable journey. 

Please note that this is an administrative page for staff use only.

Name: Division of Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion
Description:
Our goal at the Division of Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion is to build an intellectually vibrant climate that sustains the inclusiveness and engagement of our diverse community.

 

FIU is committed to providing the highest quality educational and employment experience to its students, faculty, and staff in a nurturing and supportive environment. In doing so, the institution is committed to ensuring that instruction and services are delivered in a manner that is reflective and supportive of diversity as it relates to gender, socioeconomic status, gender identity, race, ethnicity, physical and mental ability, nationality, military status, sexual orientation, spirituality, and cultural identity.

 

We encourage and expect the entire FIU community to model these values and to commit to recruiting, retaining, and supporting students, faculty, and staff who reflect the diversity of our global society.

Name: Doctoral and Masters Student Alliance
Description:
The Doctoral and Masters Student Alliance (DMSA) is a graduate-student-led University-wide organization dedicated to providing programming and advocacy for FIU's large and diverse population of graduate and professional students. DMSA aims to foster graduate students' sense of belonging to FIU through programming, increased affinity, and greater visibility. We strive to empower graduate students in our efforts to contribute to their success.

The mission of DMSA is to advocate for and celebrate graduate and professional students by coordinating activities and events that cater to our needs and desires and that stimulate student involvement and enrich campus life. DMSA also works to ensure that graduate students’ concerns are addressed to the Student Government Association and FIU Administration.

Name: Doctors & Scientists of the Future
Description: The Doctors & Scientists of the Future is an organization that aims to unite undergraduate pre-health students with the undergraduate scientific community at FIU while preparing them for graduate programs in the scientific and medical fields. This objective will be accomplished by implementing panels of scientists/doctors, enriching workshops for professional development, and socials to networking between each community. Ultimately, the club will provide benefits to students within these communities to help shape them for the future.

Name: Eclipse fashion society
Description: The purpose for this organization shall be to provide a club for those student’s that has the love for fashion design and modeling. We will provide programming within the club for our member to exercise their talents. The group will focus on design, styling, make-up artistry, cosmetology and modeling. We will put on high production runways shows to show case our collections.

Name: Eco Engineering Club
Description:
Eco Engineering Club at FIU is a student organization focused on providing opportunities for students of all majors to explore sustainable technologies and ideas. We accomplish this mission by educating our members with essential ideas and projects and participating in the Shell Eco-Marathon competition.

The Shell Eco-Marathon Competition is an opportunity for students to build a hyper-efficient vehicle by experimenting with engineering principles and sustainable technologies. Eco Engineering is currently
participating in the Prototype division to make an electric vehicle by designing and constructing critical components, such as the chassis, powertrain, steering system, and aerodynamic components among other things.

Name: Emergency Medicine Interest Group
Description: N/A

Name: Empowering Women In Law
Description:
As an organization, we act as a space for driven, like-minded students to gather and work together to achieve our law school and professional goals. We fundraise for women’s education and rights, prepare for the LSAT and law school applications, expand our professional networks, and most importantly learn about various career paths in the legal field and what it is like to be a woman in the field of law.

 

To join our group chat, click the link: 

https://chat.whatsapp.com/JXZVPkwjqhH6TInE6ialm1

Name: Engineering Campus Council
Description: The Engineering Campus Council provides support for the 5,000+ students based on the Engineering Campus so that they may continue to grow academically, develop professionally, and encourage the creation of lasting relations with peers and mentors at Florida International University.

Name: Engineers Without Borders - FIU
Description:
Engineers Without Borders USA (EWB-USA) is a national non-profit organization focused on empowering communities and ultimately building a better world through engineering projects. Our mission is to provide pathways for opportunities for struggling communities in order for them to sustainably meet their basic human needs and equip leaders to solve the world’s most pressing challenges.

Our chapter consists of FIU students of all majors, mostly civil, environmental, and mechanical engineering. We encourage those who have a passion for helping others while gaining experience with real-world projects to join our team! We are actively working on a solution for El Chimborazo’s water quality problem.

Join our WhatsApp group chat to stay updated on all things EWB!

Name: English Graduate Organization
Description:
The English Graduate Organization (EGO) is a student-run society that aims to address the needs of graduate students in FIU's English Department by providing specialized academic and professional support.

The organization seeks to promote the interests of our diverse grad student body; whether it is through academic and social events or acting as a liaison between grad students and administration/faculty, we want to promote engagement in our grad student community so that we can share our intellectual curiosity and passion for the diverse subjects we study among peers.

By creating spaces of engagement and a platform for expression, we hope to address issues in the department as they arise and create groups and activities that serve the specific needs and interests of the student body.

The English Graduate Organization comprises all English MA and MFA students. Regardless of program or specialization, all FIU graduate students can be members of this society.

Name: Entertainment Media Arts Club at FIU
Description:
Entertainment Media Arts (EMA) is a club at FIU for artists, animators, writers, musicians, audio designers, film enthusiasts, game developers, hobbyists, and more who love entertainment media and want to immerse themselves in a community with other interested individuals. This community is for those both interested in learning to create as a career or hobby and those also just interested in seeing these works come to life. It is aimed towards (but not limited to) students interested in these fields and others that fall within them:

  • Entertainment Arts
  • Game Development 
  • Animation and Film
  • Storytelling Literature 
  • Music and SFX

The entertainment industry can be very challenging to understand and break into, especially given that there are so many fields and jobs that one could aspire towards. EMA was founded with the hope that this club can help other students learn about the entertainment arts industry, get to know each other, and have fun with their shared passions along the way! Events include: 

  • Fun and casual socially-oriented events 
  • Professional development workshops
  • Talks and interviews with industry veterans
  • Collaborative and team oriented projects

EMA Contact: Email us directly at emaclub@fiu.edu! We are more than happy to answer any of your questions, connect with you for leadership opportunities, and receive suggestions on how EMA can support your creative journey. 

 

***Be sure to join our Discord via https://discord.gg/6Tpn7msVq no matter what skill level or interest feel free to drop by and learn more about us!***

Name: Environmental Health Sciences Association
Description: The objective of the EHSA at FIU is to stimulate interest in the subject of Environmental Health Sciences and create an environment for the academic and professional growth of the students by engaging in academic and community outreaches that promote public health.

Name: Everglades Hall
Description:
Everglades Hall is home to 372 upper-class students, 12 resident assistants.

Features

  • Full kitchen
  • Laundry room on 1st floor
  • Twin extra long mattress (size 36 x 80 x 6)
  • Shared bathroom

Name: F1@FIU
Description: F1@FIU is the ultimate destination for Florida International University students who share a passion for Formula 1. We provide a community for enthusiasts to come together and engage in discussions, events, and watch parties for every race. Our goal is to create an inclusive and supportive environment for all students to enjoy the sport, fostering camaraderie and a shared love for Formula 1.

Description: FMA at FIU's mission is to broaden the common interests between academicians and practitioners, provide opportunities for professional interaction between and among academicians, practitioners and students, promote the development and understanding of basic and applied research and of sound financial practices, and to enhance the quality of education in finance.

Name: Financial Wellness Program
Description:
The Financial Wellness Program aims to help our Panther community members understand the various aspects of living a financially healthy life and feel confident about their personal money management.

 

Resources, Programs and Services include:

- Workshops

- iGrad (Financial Literacy Platform)

- Fundamentals of Financial Literacy Digital Badge

- Collaboration with University Emergency Aid Initiatives

Name: FIU Army ROTC
Description: Florida International University Army ROTC is one the largest programs in the United States with over 250 participating Students and Cadets. Here you will learn firsthand what it takes to lead others, motivate groups, and succeed in any competitive environment. In addition to the skills you will obtain, you will develop friendships, relationships, and memories that will last a lifetime. Our freshman and sophomore classes are offered to all students on campus.

Name: FIU Athletics
Description:
The FIU Department of Intercollegiate Athletics adheres to the belief that intercollegiate athletics is an integral part of the educational framework of the institution and the program exists to support and compliment the mission and goals of the University. The mission of the FIU Department of Intercollegiate Athletics is to initiate, stimulate and continually improve the athletic and recreation programs for students by (1) promoting academic excellence and educational leadership, (2) striving to obtain athletic distinction at the Division 1 level, (3) assuring gender equity and cultivating diversity, (4) fostering and promoting personal integrity among its participants, (5) encouraging activities and experiences which instill the value of lifelong participation and total well-being, and (6) providing an avenue for the social development of the student through participatory interaction within and outside athletic and campus community.

In addition to augmenting the academic, athletic and personal development of students, events sponsored by the Department are conducted to facilitate unity, promote camaraderie and further social bonding within the community, foster and maintain institutional support from FIU alumni, University affiliates and external constituents positively increase the visibility of the University and Conference USA and enhance international and cultural understanding.
 
 
The Department and University fulfill these functions through the enforcement of developed and adopted eligibility rules that comply with the standards of scholarship, sportsmanship, personal conduct and amateurism. The Department strives to operate programs at the highest level of competition within budgetary constraints while respecting NCAA legislation, conference mandates, state and institutional regulations.

Participation in FIU Athletics will provide student-athletes with the opportunity to pursue a quality education in one of America's leading urban universities and develop a value system which encourages discipline, teamwork, self-confidence, leadership skills and sporting behavior in an equitable and diverse environment. Ultimately, the goal is to assure the experience that the students have in the FIU Department of Intercollegiate Athletics is profound and meaningful and serves to form a lasting bond with Florida International University.

Name: FIU Career Ready
Description: The FIU Career Ready Program provides a multi-level career preparation pathway for current students and graduates to thrive in well-paying jobs. We also celebrate our student employees with our annual Student Employee of the Year (SEOTY) Ceremony!

Name: FIU Catholic Panthers
Description: Catholic Panthers at FIU is a student-led, Catholic community of students, faculty, staff and alumni at FIU striving to grow, both personally and communally, in our relationship with God through our Catholic faith.

Name: FIU Class of 2023
Description: N/A

Name: FIU Disaster Volunteer Program
Description: In 2018, with the support of the Office of the President, the FIU Department of Emergency Management introduced the FIU Disaster Volunteers Program. The Disaster Volunteers Program is a cadre of trained and motivated FIU students, faculty, and staff who may be called upon to assist the University with sheltering operations, administrative services, logistical support, call center operations, or other disaster-related tasks either before, during, or after a disaster. Volunteers will be trained in topics such as disaster preparedness, first aid, sheltering operations, etc. As a Disaster Volunteer, individuals will have the opportunity to learn the fundamentals of emergency management, build upon their skill set, and help the University prepare for, respond to, and quickly recover from an emergency. Additionally, disaster volunteers bring varying perspective, fresh talent, and skills to emergency management that could directly support the mission.

Name: FIU Esports
Description:
FIU is launching an esports program to support university and community enthusiasts socially, academically, and professionally. 

On top of a multipurpose LAN (local area network) facility, FIU Esports will include an intramural club, a varsity league, and fresh academic pathways to the esports industry.

The esports operation and its facility promise to improve diversity in esports culture while turning FIU into South Florida’s premier gaming authority.

Name: FIU Fraternity & Sorority Life
Description: The FSL community at FIU consists of 33 fraternities and sororities made up of over 1,300 students. Each organization was founded on the values of scholarship, leadership, brotherhood/sisterhood, community service, and philanthropy.

Name: FIU Global
Description: N/A

Name: FIU Honors College
Description: The Honors College is the center of undergraduate academic excellence at FIU. We are a community of students, faculty, and staff from all backgrounds and disciplines who are dedicated to excellence in all pursuits. We offer a unique academic and social experience that is compatible with all majors, transcends disciplines, and encourages our students to become life-long learners.

Name: FIU Libraries
Description:
Need a place to work on that paper or finish that group project? Check out our quiet floors, conversation floors, and group study rooms. Need to use electronic equipment? There are desktop computers, laptops, iPads, cameras, and portable chargers available to borrow. And make sure you’re familiar with the top ten things to know about the FIU Libraries, for students and for faculty members.
 
Whether you stop by our buildings or check us out online, we hope you’ll consider the FIU Libraries to be a partner and source of quality learning during your time at FIU. Visit, explore all we have to offer and feel free to reach out with any questions or concerns.

Name: FIU Model United Nations Program
Description:
FIU MUN is Florida International University's very own Model United Nations competitive program, generously sponsored by the Student Government Association. The team has been ranked top 5 in North America for the past 10 years. It is supported by the Student Government Association at FIU-MMC and the Steven J. Green School of International and Public Affairs as well as its faculty director Dr. Mohamed Ghumrawi The FIU Model United Nations Program is an international relations course offered during both the fall and spring semesters. The course provides an interactive environment engrossing students in the different aspects of political and international affairs.

APPLICATIONS FOR FALL 2023 SEMESTER NOW OPEN, APPLY BELOW:
