Name: Pi Delta Phi
Description: Pi Delta Phi, established in 1906, is the French National Honor Society for undergraduate and graduate students at accredited public and private colleges and universities in the United States. The FIU Chapter was established in 1991. As per the Pi Delta Phi constitution, the purpose of this society is to recognize outstanding scholarship in the French language and its literature; to increase the knowledge and appreciation of Americans for the cultural contributions of the French-speaking world; and to stimulate and encourage French cultural activities. The motto of this society is: Probaínomen Diakritoi Philogálatoi, which means "Avançons, amis fidèles de la culture française".

Name: Pi Kappa Alpha
Description: N/A

Name: Pi Kappa Phi
Description:
MEN OF C.L.A.S.S.

CHARACTER

A wise man once said, you are judged by the company you keep. You can be certain that with Pi Kappa Phi, you are in good company. We share more than a house or greek letters but principled behavior and values. You can own the courage to stand up for your beliefs and act upon your morals and convictions. For Pi Kappa Phi these values are not only encouraged – it is an obligation of our membership.

Every member of Pi Kappa Phi is expected to:

· Forbid hazing in any form.

· Exhibit ultimate respect for each individual brother.

· Act responsibly in every situation.

· Be confident in what he believes and have courage to stand up for what is right.

LEADERSHIP

A college education is more than just attending classes. Some of the greatest lessons you will learn are from the leadership opportunities outside the classroom. With Pi Kappa Phi you will experience the best in leadership and personal development with opportunities ranging from corporate-level leadership training to leadership through service, Pi Kapps gain valuable real-world experience.

ACHIEVEMENT

It’s not only the feeling of winning Homecoming or capturing first place in an intramural championship game. Achievement is about selfless contribution towards a noble cause. Winning is not as important as being able to shake your opponent’s hand after the match. Integrity and determination are the skills and traits needed to become a better student, leader, citizen, and fraternity man.

SCHOLARSHIP

College isn’t easy. Juggling chapter meetings, spending time with friends, and finding time to study is no easy task. That’s why Pi Kappa Phi provides its members with an Academic Coach – a faculty member paid and trained by the National Headquarters to be your academic resource. Intellectual growth is important to Pi Kappa Phi and our opportunities are meant to help you reach your academic potential.

SERVICE

In case you haven’t figured it out already, Pi Kappa Phi is not your typical fraternity. It was this pioneering spirit that led us to the creation of a one of a kind philanthropy – Push America. Since 1977, Push America’s mission has been to improve the lives of people with disabilities. Pi Kappa Phi remains the only fraternity to create and maintain its own national philanthropy. The Journey of Hope is the single largest fraternity fund-raising event. Pi Kappa Phi’s raise $350,000+ per year, and over 500 Pi Kapps have ridden bicycles across the United States on behalf of people with disabilities.

Name: Pi Sigma Alpha Tau Rho
Description: Pi Sigma Alpha Tau Rho is FIU's chapter of the national political science honor society. We are a group that has a passion for politics and policy. According to our national organization, PSA "hosts chapters on nearly 850 campuses and has inducted more than 300,000 members."

The purpose is to support the development of occupational sciences and the practice of authentic occupational therapy by promoting research and other scholarly activities by its members. In this way, the organization serves not only the profession, but helps to insure quality health care services for the general public.

Through our energetic, ambitious & motivated attitudes, we set out to mobilize & demand change from our elected officials to listen to our voices and urge our peers to join us in our national advocacy campaigns!

Name: Power U for social change at FIU
Description:
Mission & Purpose

The Mission of Power U for Social change at FIU will be to organize and develop the leadership of young Adults especially Black and Brown young adults and Black women at FIU so that they may help lead the struggle to liberate all oppressed people.

The purpose of this organization shall be to organize to enhance students’ ability to fight for social change at FIU by promoting organizing, educating, and leadership building within the student body to play an influential role in the movement of social justice.

Description:

Follow us on Instagram to join the club and to see our events @pre.optometryfiu

Description: Welcome to the Pre-Law Advising and Training Office (PLATO) website where you will find helpful information to assist you in your pursuit of a career in law. PLATO offers a variety of resources, seminars, workshops, events and advising services to prepare students for the law school admissions process, their first year as a law school student and the academic rigors of law school.

Description: The American Medical Student Association is committed to improving health care and health care delivery to all people; promoting active improvement in medical education; involving its members in the social, moral and ethical obligations of the profession of medicine; assisting in the improvement and understanding of world health problems; contributing to the welfare of medical students, premedical students, interns, residents and post-MD/DO trainees; and advancing the profession of medicine.

Name: Pre-Therapy Students Association
Description:
(Please follow our Instagram @PTSAFIU for the quickest replies and updates)

The Pre-Therapy Students Association (PTSA) is a unique interactive medium through which FIU students will explore the various careers associated with the field of therapy all in one place! Our mission is educating, informing, and uplifting students who wish to pursue a career in health and identify with the various benefits and opportunities within the therapy field. Our purpose lies in the collaboration of the student body to reach their full potential. PTSA will aid students decide which professional field is right for them through study groups focused on pre-requisite courses, informational meetings for every field, shadowing in all areas, volunteering in the community, and workshops directed towards those fields which include but are not limited to: Occupational Therapy, Physical Therapy, Athletic Training, Speech Therapy, Recreational Therapy, and Health Administration. PTSA’s goal is to supplement the student experience prior to their enrollment in graduate-level education while introducing students from various majors and career paths to the benefits and vast opportunities within the therapy field. Our organization’s aim is to inform, empower, and better guide students about the opportunities available within the field of Therapy. If you are someone who is interested in helping others, working in a variety of settings from home-health agencies, private offices, clinics, nursing homes, or hospitals; then this club is for you. Our members would receive invaluable knowledge and experience through our meetings with hands-on activities, and interactive exchanges with speakers that have rich inside information on the therapeutic industry as a career. Through collaborations with centers and professionals in the field, and contact with FIU graduates or those who soon will be, our club will show you the numerous benefits that can be attained through these growing careers, as well as give you high-level instructions on how to reach the goals you want to achieve within your aspiring programs.

Name: Pre-Veterinary Society
Description: This student society aims to help members in all aspects related to attaining and achieving the necessary skills to gain entrance into a Veterinary School. The Pre-Veterinary Society provides a wide range of opportunities for members to gain not only the hands-on learning experience but also personal and leadership growth. Several different aspects of veterinary medicine are explored through community service events, vet school admission representatives, veterinarian guest speakers, and job shadowing. As a diverse society, our community service activities are not limited to animal related endeavors. Members of the Pre-Veterinary Society have an advantage of making an array of friends that share their passion for the Veterinary field. At the core of this organization, there is an abundance of animal lovers helping their community and each other to fulfill our dreams of saving the world, one species at a time.

Name: Pride Student Union
Description:
The Pride Student Union (PSU) is a student-led University-wide programming bureau under the Student Government Association (SGA) that is dedicated to providing cultural, educational, and social programming to the University community.

 

The purpose of PSU is to educate, uplift, engage, and promote pride and solidarity for and on behalf of 2SLGBTQIA+, SGL, and allied communities at FIU. PSU also strives to empower the student body in their efforts to make the most of their college experience, contribute to student success and equity, and promote unity.

 

The mission of PSU is to create a brave space where students, regardless of their gender or sexuality, can learn and grow to their fullest potential. PSU aims to foster students' sense of belonging to FIU through increased affinity and visibility. PSU seeks the creation of student leadership opportunities through the unification of university-wide gender-related, sexuality-related, and sexual health-related programming. PSU also serves as a bridge and unified voice addressing the concerns of the student body to the SGA and the FIU Administration.

Interested in collaborating with us? Fill out our Collaboration Request Form at least 6 weeks in advance of your proposed event/activity!

Name: Psi Chi
Description:
Psi Chi is the International Honor Society in Psychology. Our mission is to recognize and promote excellence in the science and application of psychology. Our purpose is to encourage, stimulate, and maintain excellence in the scholarship of the individual members in all fields, particularly in psychology, and to advance the science of psychology.

Psi Chi is committed to diversity and inclusion in all of its forms through research; clinical, community, and professional applications; education; mentorship; and organizational leadership. As scholars and practitioners in the field of psychology, we recognize the rich and nuanced factors that contribute to the expression of prejudice, including social, community, familial, and psychological processes. Findings from psychological science and related fields document numerous negative consequences to the mental health and wellbeing of individuals and communities from exposure to discrimination, whether temporary or chronic. 

As an organization, we work to address all forms of hate and oppression, including racial, ethnic, and gender inequality, refugee and immigrant bias, religious prejudice, sexual harassment and sexual violence, social class marginalization, biases related to sexual orientation and gender identity, age, physical and other disabilities among many others. We believe that our mission can be fulfilled only by supporting and encouraging people of varied racial, ethnic, gender identity, sexual orientation, and social class backgrounds to both participate in conducting psychological research, education, practice, training, and service, and to recognize and value diverse people within these contexts. The scope of our organizational relevance is only as broad as the diversity of our membership and their scholarly pursuits.

Name: Psychology Ambassadors for Student Success
Description:
PASS is a student organization that seeks to promote student performance, career preparation and professional development in the field of Psychology. Efforts to improve undergraduate performance and retention, and to encourage professional development skills mainly with respect to post-Baccalaureate field(s) of study include, but are not limited to: raising Grade Point Averages, (i.e. teaching study skills and/or test-taking strategies, facilitating study groups), informing students about post-undergraduate career options, updating students on developments within the field of Psychology, suggesting academic tracks within the Department, promoting research and test-preparation opportunities and facilitating mentorship. A secondary goal of PASS (with the aid of related psychology organizations), we shall seek to identify student concerns over FIU’s Department of Psychology and methods for better-improving communication between the undergraduate students, administrative staff, and faculty.

 

Requirements to join PASS:

  • Must be an enrolled FIU student  and
    enrolled in minimally 9 credits (per semester).
  • Minimum GPA of a 2.0
  • Recommended to have Wednesdays available

 

In order to remain as an active member, members must:

  • Attend 50 percent of meetings and have 25 percent
    attendance at PASS events per semester 
  • A total of 6 points must be accumulated per semester in order to evaluate membership (and to be inducted into PASS)

For more information please email us or visit Documents >click on "Constitution/Bylaws" with the most updated year. 

2022 Resource Sheet

Name: Relay for Life
Description: FIU Relay for Life is a unique overnight celebration of life and hope that one day we will find a cure for cancer. Proceeds benefit the American Cancer Society. No matter who you are, there's a place for you at Relay. Each dollar you raise will help save lives. How far will you go to make a difference in the fight against cancer? Your reasons for walking in Relay For Life are as unique and special as the story that motivates you. This is your opportunity to not only honor cancer survivors and remember people we have lost, but also to raise funds and awareness to help save lives. Because of your support, we are creating a world where cancer can't claim another year of anyone's life. You are helping create a world with less cancer and more birthdays!

Name: Residence Hall Association - RHA
Description:
The Residence Hall Association (or RHA) is the governing student body and voice of the on-campus student population. RHA assists the Department of Housing and Residential Experience in fostering the educational and social pursuit of a diverse student population, and represents them to the community at large. RHA offers unique opportunities for student growth and development, as well as leadership experiences through programming and other student-related activities. All students who live on campus at FIU-MMC are considered RHA members and are encouraged to get involved!

Within RHA, each residential community hosts a Hall or Community Council. The RHA Councils are the student government bodies for a specific residential community. These Councils represent the voice of the residents of its community, advocates for their needs, and provides student input. RHA Councils facilitate and support quality programs and service events for the residents in the building. They also provide residents with opportunities for leadership development. 

Through involvement in RHA Councils, students learn how to be active members of a community, how to advocate for themselves and others, and how to affect change in their community. They develop leadership skills, gain a sense of belonging and importance, grow personally, and learn about self-authorship. RHA Councils can be an essential tool in teaching students how to become future engaged citizens and leaders.

RHA supports its sister organization, the National Residence Hall Honorary (or NRHH). NRHH is the only national organization that exclusively recognizes leaders within residence halls. It is also considered the recognition branch for the national student housing organization known as the National Association of College and University Residence Halls, Inc. (or NACURH). At FIU, we host the Golden Panther chapter of NRHH, which serves to give local, regional, and national recognition to students making outstanding contributions to the FIU campus and residence halls. NRHH is exclusively driven by the overarching values of recognition and service to others.

Name: Roarthon
Description:
Roarthon, FIU’s Dance Marathon, is a year-long fundraising campaign ending in a 12-hour dance party. All the funds raised benefit the Children's Miracle Network Hospitals program at Nicklaus Children's Hospital Foundation, the fundraising arm of Nicklaus Children's Hospital. Children's Miracle Network Hospitals is a non-profit organization dedicated to saving and improving the lives of children by raising funds and awareness for 170 children's hospitals throughout North America. Since 1985, Nicklaus has been the only Children's Miracle Network Hospital in South Florida. Over 300 students participate in the 17-hour fundraiser that takes an entire year and a committee of 50 plus students to plan and activate. As of 2017, the FIU community has raised over 1.5 million dollars!

Roarthon 2024 will be held on April 6 at the MMC Wellness & Recreation Center.

Visit events.dancemarathon.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=donorDrive.event&eventID=5752 

to learn how you can get involved!

Name: Robert Stempel College of Public Health & Social Work
Description:
Advancing your education to be a force for good demands dedication and guidance. At the Robert Stempel College of Public Health and Social Work, explore the interconnectivity of social, biological, environmental and cultural elements of health to be a force for positive change.

Our researchers are looking for solutions to local and global public health issues. From neurological brain behavior to health disparities, oxidative stress to tobacco smoking – students at Stempel College have the opportunity to get firsthand experience in state-of the- art research facilities as they participate in groundbreaking discoveries.

Stempel College is home to top-ranked undergraduate and graduate programs in dietetics and nutrition, public health, social work, and disaster management.

Name: Sales Society (1)
Description:
To develop people both personally and professionally in the warmest and welcoming manner. Regardless of career path or personality, we strive to keep our members ahead of their peers.We provide both business and nonbusiness students with a better understanding of sales as a profession with a venue for further developing their interpersonal, networking, presentation, objection handling, closing and negotiation skills. Using workshops, panel discussions, job shadows, onsite visits and networking event settings facilitated by corporate guest speakers and sales professionals, students can practice these skills, enabling them to become confident and ethical sales and service professionals.  

The Sales Society will host workshops and sales tournaments each semester, facilitated by guests and partners from the business community. Speakers will provide hands-on learning exercises targeted to develop sales skills such as questioning, networking, negotiating, interviewing, and closing to students of Florida International University.To promote the awareness and development of the FIU Sales Society, FIU Sales Program, and the FIU Sales Team at Florida International University.

Name: School Psychology Student Association
Description: SPSA is a graduate organization that exists to promote positive relationships and educate school psychology graduate students at FIU. All school psychology students, professors, interested students, and alumni are invited to become members.

Name: Service and Awareness for Neurodegenerative Diseases
Description:
Our Purpose: The purpose of SAND is to promote understanding, recognition, and support for individuals affected by neurodegenerative diseases through educational awareness and community service. Specifically, SAND will:

  1. Educate our university and community on neurodegenerative diseases, potential remedies, and what can be done to help.
  2. Be a service oriented organization. SAND will visit local nursing facilities and interact with residents and families who have been impacted by neurodegenerative diseases. The organization will also partake in fundraisers and donation drives to support those who have been affected by neurodegenerative diseases.
  3. Support both local and national research and clinical efforts to help in the domain of neurodegenerative diseases and the elderly.

How you can get involved: Add us on PantherConnect to receive emails for meetings, events, and more! Additionally, reach out to us on Instagram (@sand.fiu) or contact our President to be added to our WhatsApp group chat!

Sigma Gamma Rho was founded November 12, 1922 at Butler University, Indianapolis, Indiana. Omicron Theta was chartered on the campus of Florida International University on November 23, 1997.

Name: Sigma Iota Rho
Description: Sigma Iota Rho's mission is to promote and reward scholarship and service among students and practitioners of international studies, international affairs, and global studies, and to foster integrity and creative performance in the conduct of world affairs. Sigma Iota Rho provides an excellent opportunity for students to learn about the numerous different post-graduate options available to them. It also has a variety of resources available to its members so that they can better advance their academic and professional interests.

Name: Sigma Kappa
Description: The purpose of Sigma Kappa Sorority is to provide women lifelong opportunities and support for social, intellectual, and spiritual development by bringing women together to positively impact our communities.

Name: Sigma Lambda Beta International Fraternity, Inc.
Description:
Welcome to Sigma Lambda Beta!
We are the G.R.I.M.E.Y. Theta Delta Chapter. For over 35 years our organization has grown into the largest Latino-based fraternity with a multi-cultural membership with more than 14K members Worldwide.

Our Fraternity was founded in April 4, 1986, at the University of Iowa. We are a social organization that promotes diverse cultures and the development of our brothers, we take pride not only the recognition, but the intersection of these four principles: Brotherhood, Scholarship, Cultural Awareness, and Community Service.

Our Brotherhood has the support of two nonprofits:
1) SIGMA LAMBDA BETA EDUCATION FOUNDATION= Distributes funds for educational programming and scholarships for Brothers.
2) SIGMA LAMBDA BETA OMEGA FUND= Provides financial assistance to the families of Brothers at the time of their death.

 

Opportunity for Wisdom, Wisdom for Culture

Name: Sigma Lambda Gamma National Sorority, Inc.
Description:
We are the FEARLESS Phi Gamma Chapter of Sigma Lambda Gamma National Sorority, Incorporated. Sigma Lambda Gamma was established at the University of Iowa in Iowa City, Iowa on April 9, 1990 and established at Florida International University in Miami, FL on June 16, 2006.

We are the largest and fastest growing multicultural sorority in the nation! We are a social organization that promotes our evolving and diverse cultures by sharing them through our 5 principles: Academics, Community Service, Cultural Awareness, Morals & Ethics, and Social Interaction.

Name: Sigma Phi Epsilon
Description: SigEp is reshaping the definition of a fraternity by offering a top-notch student experience during one of the most significant periods of a man's life. Our focus is on enhancing a man's education by helping him strengthen his character, build leadership and interpersonal skills, and cultivate healthy, lifelong relationships that are vital to a prosperous and satisfying life.

Name: SOBEWFF Volunteer Program
Description:
“Helped execute one of the nation’s premiere food and beverage events alongside the world’s most renowned wine and spirits producers, chefs and culinary personalities.”

 

That’s the opportunity you’ll have as a student volunteer at the Food Network & Cooking Channel South Beach Wine & Food Festival presented by Capital One! It’s invaluable experiential learning that will prepare you for the workforce like no other.

 

Approximately 1,200 volunteers help make the Festival happen every year and assist with raising about $2 million annually to support the Chaplin School of Hospitality & Tourism Management and student success at FIU. The Festival offers real-world, hands-on experience in a variety of areas – including, but not limited to, event management, logistics, inventory, culinary, and guest registration.

 

SOBEWFF® 2020 Recap Video

 

Available Volunteer Roles

Volunteer Roles vary from event to event, but fall under four main categories:

  • Leads
    Work alongside Event Managers and production teams, and manage volunteers.
  • Front of house (FOH)
    Guest registration, talent ambassadors, survey team, auction associates, and general event support.
  • Back of house (BOH)
    Assist with roles such as logistics, set-up, break-down, inventory, and golf cart driving.
  • Culinary
    Provide culinary support to chefs including plating and baking & pastry.

Stay up-to-date for when SOBEWFF® 2022 recruitment starts by following us at @SOBEWFFvolunteers!

Name: Soccer Club
Description: The FIU Soccer Club at Florida International University is a dynamic and inclusive community fostering sportsmanship, teamwork, and excellence through soccer. Open to all at FIU, it offers members the chance to enhance their soccer skills and build lifelong friendships. The club organizes various activities, including tournaments, community outreach programs, and workshops with notable soccer personalities, aiming to develop members holistically. Guided by experienced mentors, it seeks to create a nurturing environment where each member feels valued and an integral part of a family united by a love for soccer.

Name: Society for Sustainable Souls
Description: We discuss topics such as zero-waste, fast fashion, composting, plant-based eating, and other sustainable tips and tricks, in addition to civic engagement in our local community.

Name: Society for Women in Marine Science @ FIU
Description:
Hello all! Welcome to the Society for Women in Marine Science or SWMS Club page. The goal of the SWMS club is to inform and involve students who are interested in marine life or just biology in general. SWMS also seeks to celebrate the exciting and vital science conducted by women locally and around the globe, with an emphasis on establishing meaningful connections among women and minorities across ocean science.

 

Description

The purpose of SWMS will be to inspire and educate future marine biologists and scientists on matters of professional development, networking, and conservation of marine systems. It will provide opportunities for research and volunteer work in the marine field and will raise awareness of the ever-growing problems facing our oceans. Additionally, it will provide a setting where like-minded students can share their passion for marine biology.

 

 

 

Thank you!

Name: Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers
Description: SHPE changes lives by empowering the Hispanic community to realize its fullest potential and to impact the world through STEM awareness, access, support and development.

Name: Society of Manufacturing Engineers @ FIU
Description:
The purpose of SME @ FIU is to empower engineering students to obtain and develop the necessary knowledge, skills, and experience to become successful and productive in the field of manufacturing engineering. Such knowledge and skills will not be limited to hands-on engineering experience obtained in workshops and lectures by engineers in the field. Our activities will also provide the networking, entrepreneurial, and community outreach experiences that will make SME @ FIU members an integral part of our engineering field.

By being members of SME, students can connect with the top level, experienced personnel from industries. FIU Mechanical and Materials Engineering department can augment their industrial partners pool. This will help senior design students to work on real-time industrial project towards their degree program.

Name: Society of Professional Journalists at FIU
Description: SPJ at FIU is a journalism club connecting student journalists with industry professionals and instilling the importance of sustaining a free press in future journalists.

Name: Society of Women Engineers
Description: The Society of Women Engineers (SWE) is a not-for-profit educational and service organization that empowers women to succeed and advance in the field of STEM, and to be recognized for their life-changing contributions as engineers and leaders. Founded in 1950, SWE is the driving force that establishes engineering as a highly desirable career for women through an exciting array of training and development programs, networking opportunities, scholarships, outreach and advocacy activities, and much more.

Name: Sociology, Anthropology, and Geography Graduate Student Association
Description: The purpose of this organization shall be to promote networking and enhancement in learning in the fields of sociology, anthropology, and geography. SAGGSA engages students and faculty and the wider FIU community in contemporary issues in research and in social and political participation through regular events and a colloquium series. Drives are held to help those in need in the community as a way to stay active citizens in the Miami area and around the world.

Name: SORC (Student Organization Resource Center)
Description:
The Student Organization Resource Center (SORC) is located in GC 2302 next to the Campus Life office.

Unfortunately do to the coronavirus pandemic our office is closed.

Name: Special Olympics Unified Sports Club
Description: Special Olympics College Clubs function as an official student organization on campus and are led by students with and without intellectual disabilities. Members of a Special Olympics College Club gain experience participating in Unified Sports and hosting Special Olympics events thus creating meaningful inclusion of people with and without intellectual disabilities in the campus community.

Name: Sport Clubs
Description: A sport club is a group of students who meet regularly to pursue an interest in various sports activities, either competitively, instructionally, or recreationally. Many clubs offer the opportunity to compete against other schools at the state and national level through national governing bodies. Sport clubs are created and managed by students, providing unique opportunities for members to develop athletic and leadership skills; often the success of a Sport Club is dependent on the leadership abilities of club officers and members.

Name: Sport Science Organization
Description: The Sport Science Organization is an academic extra curricular organization based around physical education, sports, fitness and wellness. The organization's goal is to help students interested in fields physical education and sports and fitness to further develop their skills, gain real world experiences and expand their network. It is open to all FIU students and free to join. We host events such as fairs, guest speakers, study groups, fundraisers, volunteer activities, lab days and social gatherings, all themed around exercise and wellness promotion.

Name: StartUP FIU
Description: StartUP FIU is a university-wide innovation hub that fosters and develops entrepreneurship and innovation to help our students, researchers, and community connect, contribute to, and thrive in today’s fast-changing world. We create and run programs based on two foundational beliefs: that the skills and principles of entrepreneurship are essential to navigate and harness the opportunities of our disruptive age, and that universities can play a unique role in unlocking opportunity and unleashing potential to shape a better, more inclusive, and more innovative future.

Name: Stempel Public Health Association
Description:
Welcome to the Stempel Public Health Association (SPHA). We are a student-run organization of the FIU Robert Stempel College of Public Health and Social Work.

Our Goal is to foster innovation by enriching the educational experience and professional development of graduate students. We provide a Public Health platform for the FIU community where students and alumni are encouraged to actively participate. 

This organization is open to all FIU students and faculty members. We strive to educate the campus community and increase awareness of public health. 

"Because Public Health means Your Health."

Together for the greater good.

Name: Steven J. Green School of International & Public Affairs
Description: N/A

Name: STITCH (Students Taking Initiative Through Collaboration in Health)
Description:
🥼 Our Story

This organization within the Honors College was created for undergraduate students on any pre-health track. We hold the foundation of teamwork and support during our challenging pre-health journey. We provide opportunities to expand your knowledge in the medical field while helping out our community. As a member of STITCH, you will experience an environment that will motivate you to learn and grow to become more than a strong applicant. With us begins your journey of expanding your knowledge and cementing values.

 

🥼 Our Vision

We are committed to inspiring pre-health students and collaborating with them to create a future generation of accomplished, altruistic, and passionate health professionals.

 

🥼 Our Mission

We strive to create an exceptional experience for FIU Honors College students interested in healthcare by connecting them with opportunities that will better prepare them for medical school, nursing school, PA school, dental school, etc.

 

🥼 Our Values 

STITCH strives for empathy, teamwork, drive, community, academic excellence, and growth. At STITCH, we encourage curiosity and curate passions under manners of integrity and respect. 

 

🥼 What We Offer

  • Presentations by speakers in the medical community
  • Honors College Engagement and Service Requirements opportunities
  • Volunteer opportunities
  • Shadowing opportunities
  • Research opportunities
  • Workshops
  • Social events
  • Networking opportunities
  • Guidance and community

 

🥼 How To Join

  • Be a part of the Honors College at FIU
  • Be in good academic standing at the university
  • Have an interest in areas of healthcare
  • Fill out the application form under "Forms"

 

🥼 Contact Us

  • Check out our website for more information
  • Follow us on Instagram at @fiustitch to stay updated
  • Reach out at honorstitch@gmail.com if you have any questions

 

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jHF_jliaSX0

Name: Student Access & Success
Description: Florida International University believes that scholarship and teaching are best fulfilled when shaped by an inclusive environment. The Office of Student Access & Success is committed to improving students’ learning and success by providing engaged learning experiences through meaningful and strategic programming and services that will facilitate successful transitions between pre-collegiate, undergraduate and graduate education.

Name: Student Affairs Test Portal
Description: N/A

Name: Student Alliance for Autoimmune Awareness
Description: At Student Alliance for Autoimmune Awareness, our mission is to foster a community of passionate and dedicated premedical students, committed to making a meaningful impact in the field of autoimmune awareness, through innovative educational initiatives, engaging fundraising campaigns, hands-on research experiences, and purposeful volunteer projects. Our association strives to raise awareness about autoimmune diseases, supporting cutting-edge research, and providing opportunities for personal and professional growth through shadowing experiences and mentorship programs. Together, we aim to create future healthcare leaders who will advance the understanding and treatment of autoimmune conditions while making a positive difference in the lives of those affected by these challenging diseases.

Name: Student Ambassadors
Description: Florida International University (FIU) Student Ambassadors are a select group of students who serve as hosts and hostesses for visiting dignitaries at numerous university and community functions. These events may include conferences held at FIU, convocations, guest lectures, athletic tailgates, President’s Council meetings, campus tours, Regan House tours and the annual Torch Awards Gala. The offices of the President, Vice Presidents, Deans, Alumni Relations and other prominent areas within FIU work with Ambassadors for their various needs. Student Ambassadors are vital to the mission of the university.

Name: Student Government Association
Description: Student Government Association (SGA) is the organization that represents the voices of the FIU students. Our purpose is to serve as the governing body responsible for representing the students' interests as well as addressing student needs on matters of University, county and state concerns. SGA works closely with other student organizations and councils, in addition to being responsible for the allocation of $20 million in student fees.

Name: Student Leadership
Description: A portal for FIU student leaders across multiple divisions and organizations.

Name: Student Life and Development
Description: N/A

Name: Student Nurses' Association
Description: This organization is a constituent of Florida International University. As such, it functions as a representative body for all nursing students. The executive board aims to address the questions, comments, concerns, and ideas, through communication with faculty, staff, and administration. As an organization, we involve nursing students in community events and opportunities to grow as students and future nurses!

Name: Student Occupational Therapy Association
Description: Florida International University Student Occupational Therapy Association (SOTA) advocates for the OT profession, expands educational opportunities of the student body, and serves the community through volunteering, fundraising, and networking events.

Name: Student Programming Council
Description: The Student Programming Council is an agency that programs events for the FIU community at MMC, BBC, EC and FIU at I-75. Events can range from comedy shows to movies, from concerts to pool parties, lectures and more. Members of SPC have the opportunity to gain leadership experience, network, and learn how to program a variety of events. In addition, the agency works with other organizations on campus to provide more diverse programming to students.

Name: Student Social Work Association
Description: The Student Social Work Association (SSWA) is a service organization which seeks to promote the goals of social work through acts of service and philanthropy at FIU and throughout the Miami-Dade community. SSWA is open to anyone interested in community service or in the profession of social work.

Name: Student Support Services Club
Description: Student Support Services Club (SSSC) provides opportunities for academic development, assistance with basic college requirements, and motivates students toward the successful completion of their bachelor degree. The goal of SSSC is to increase the college retention and graduation rates of its participants.

Name: Student Veterans of America at FIU
Description:
Mission: To provide resources, support, and advocacy for Veterans, Active-Duty Military, Military Dependents, and Veteran-friendly students so that they may achieve their academic and professional goals.

Vision: To provide all veterans and military dependents with a large community to become involved in.

Name: Student's American Rehabilitation Counseling Association at Florida International University
Description: SARCA@ FIU  is a graduate student organization with a focus on providing resources, counseling, and support for individuals with disabilities and their allies. SARCA volunteers in the community to assist individuals with disabilities in an array of areas. SARCA's purpose is not only to support these individuals but to advocate for them and their support systems, and to educate society on their strength's instead of their limitations.

Name: Students for Life at FIU
Description:
Students for Life at FIU is an official club under Students for Life of America, a national organization that seeks to empower students to support pregnant and parenting students on campus and educate their community on the issue of abortion. 

Students for Life of America is a pro-life organization aiming to ending abortion across Florida and the United States.

Name: Students for Life at Florida International University
Description: Students for Life at Florida International University exists to educate, enlighten, and embolden students in their effort to uphold the right to life of all people: young, old, born, and preborn. We will advocate for the rights of all innocent human life to live and be supported, especially those of the unborn from the moment of conception and those of expectant mothers through efforts aimed to end abortion.

Name: Students in Graduate Mathematics Association
Description: Student Organization centered around facilitating the communication and interactions between graduate students in mathematics though educational and recreational activities.

Name: Surf Club
Description:
The FIU Surf and Water Boardsports Club, or FIU Surf, aims to create an environment of fun, competition, and respect for nature.

We organize a variety of events: Surf Lessons, Surf Sessions, Surf Trips, or silly ones like movie nights and skate sessions when there are no waves!

 

We’re also working toward offering more opportunities for those rippers who want to compete. Whether it’s representing FIU on the NSSA or independent tournaments, we’ll help you get there and shred those waves!

 

Even if you’ve never touched a surfboard before, you’re invited to join this community. Who knows, you might find a new love for the ocean!

Sign up here! https://forms.gle/rPb9GtKoJFHBqCeU6

Name: Sustainable Panther Network
Description: The mission of the Sustainable Panther Network (SPN) foster a sense of optimism and urgency to accelerate the culture of environmental stewardship at Florida International University by connecting students with SGA, eco-conscious student organizations, and mentors from academia, administration, and alumni networks with an aim to significantly reduce FIU’s negative impacts on the natural environment.

Name: Table Tennis Club
Description:
Welcome to the vibrant world of the Florida International University  Table Tennis Sports Club – a dynamic and engaging community where passion for table tennis meets the thrill of competition and the joy of camaraderie.

The FIU Table Tennis Sports Club is more than just a place to play; it's a hub of energy, skill, and sportsmanship. Nestled within the bustling campus of FIU, the club serves as a melting pot for table tennis enthusiasts of all levels – from beginners eager to learn the art of the game to seasoned players looking to hone their techniques and strategies.

Name: Tau Beta Pi
Description: Tau Beta Pi is the only engineering honor society representing the entire engineering profession. It is the nation's second-oldest honor society, founded at Lehigh University in 1885 to mark in a fitting manner those who have conferred honor upon their Alma Mater by distinguished scholarship and exemplary character as students in engineering, or by their attainments as alumni in the field of engineering, and to foster a spirit of liberal culture in engineering colleges.

Name: Team Students Against Violence
Description: • To involve youth in service projects and allow them to express themselves through various arts programs to foster the creation of model citizens

Name: Tennis Club
Description: We are on a mission to build a strong community of tennis players at Florida International University. All levels of play are welcome. Even if you are just starting, we will work closely with you to make you improve your game. We will be having practices to develop every aspect of your game, from fundamentals like footwork to advanced skills like the backhand slice shot.

Name: Test Portal
Description: N/A

Name: The Coffee Guild
Description:
Coffee Guild @ FIU Description-

This student-run organization expands students’ knowledge and appreciation of the wonderful world of coffee. We are open to 18+ and hold weekly meetings on Thursdays at 5:30 (on the same week as Bartenders Guild at FIU) at the BBC Chaplin School Restaurant Lab. We end our meetings with a fun trivia game called "Kahoot" and the winner of the game wins the prize(s) of the week!

Meetings will include guest speakers, tastings, and practice the basics of coffee.

Expand your curiosity at palate with us starting Fall 2023!

Name: the Epsilon Chapter of Lambda Alpha at F.I.U.
Description: The local chapter of Lambda Alpha National Honor Society will bring anthropology majors and minors together and have them organize events to serve the F.I.U. community on important topics such as cultural diversity, embracing our differences, learning from each other, and appreciating diverse cultures at FIU campus and around the world.

Name: The Language & Culture Appreciation Club
Description:
The purpose of the L&CAC @ FIU is to promote cultural awareness, language learning, and intercultural exchange among its members.

The Club aims to serve as a safe and inclusive space for those with an interest in linguistics and cultural understanding.
We work to actively promote discussion, exploration, and
participation in the form of events that provide opportunities to honor and learn about the diverse languages and cultures that exist in the world.

We aim to become a bridge between the FIU student body and the local community of language learners & underrepresented cultural groups alike!

Name: The National Association of Minority Landscape Architects at FIU
Description: NAMLA Student Chapter at FIU is the student chapter affiliated with The National Association of Minority Landscape (NAMLA) which is a 501(c)(3) organization. NAMLA at FIU looks to understand the needs, desires, and attitudes of the student body within the department of landscape architecture. Our mission is to provide a culture that allows everyone to feel represented by increasing minority representation at all levels of landscape architecture practice and academia. NAMLA’s at FIU purpose is to guide and expose students to the academic and professional communities of landscape architecture by providing educational and career development assistance to minorities Landscape Architect students and members while confronting the structural racism that has disproportionately kept people of color and minority members from having decision-making roles on how our landscapes are programmed, designed, and taught. NAMLA at FIU seeks to empower our student chapter and members to foster justice and equity in communities of minorities through education, outreach, community advocacy, community engagement, professional development, and design justice. This shall be accomplished through, but not limited to outreach education, career development, research, scholarships, financial and grant opportunities, and volunteer events designed to serve underrepresented communities.

Name: The National Society of Black Women In Medicine, Inc.
Description: The National Society of Black Women in Medicine is a multi-disciplined organization that works to increase the retention of underrepresented minority women pursuing careers in healthcare and basic science, while simultaneously promoting the advancement of those already established in these fields.

Name: The Office of National Student Exchange
Description: The National Student Exchange (NSE) is a program for undergraduate exchange within the United States and Canada. Instead of crossing oceans, NSE students cross state, regional, provincial and cultural borders. The program provides an exciting opportunity to attend one of 170 colleges and universities at in-state tuition or at little or no more cost than you now pay!

Name: The Social Justice Badge Program
Description:
Individuals who take part or complete this program will:

  •  Demonstrate understanding of social injustices and inequities;
  •  Identify proposed approaches toward remediation and/or resolution;
  •  Create an understanding across cultural differences;
  •  Address social injustices and inequities in innovative, integrative, analytical, and ethical ways;
  •  Engage independently and reflectively in life-long learning;
  •  Identify personal biases and develop techniques on how to mitigate them; and
  •  Serve, collaborate, and lead our FIU community as an advocate for positive change.

Below you will find the dates and times of all the badge workshops offered during the semester.

Fall 2023 Schedule 

Contact Us

If you have any questions, please contact the Office of Social Justice and Inclusion (OSJI) at osji@fiu.edu or by phone at (305)348-2436. 

We look forward to you attending!

Name: The Soustainability Club
Description: The purpose of this club is to give students the tools to make sustainable choices in and outside of the home via cooking lessons, engaging with local hospitality communities that share the same passion, and more regarding sustainability and the hospitality/tourism industry!

Name: The Trinity Coterie
Description: N/A

Name: The Wine Guild
Description:
FIU Club Website Wine Guild Description-

 

This student-run organization expands students’ knowledge and appreciation in the wonderful world of wine. We are open to 18+ and hold weekly meetings on Tuesdays at 5:30 (alternating with the Bartenders Guild at FIU) at the BBC Chaplin School Restaurant Lab. We end our meetings with a fun trivia game called "Kahoot" and the winner of the game wins the prize(s) of the week!

Meetings will include guest speakers, tastings, and practice the basics of wine as well as sommelier skills.

Expand your curiosity at Palate with us starting Fall 2023!

Name: The Women's Network
Description: The Women’s Network is the largest collegiate women’s networking organization in the nation. TWN’s mission is to support collegiate and recently graduated women and celebrate ambition. The Network hosts experiential events to build relationships and to authentically connect with peers, mentors, and industry leaders.

Name: Theta Alpha Kappa
Description: Religious Studies Honors Society

Name: Theta Nu Xi Multicultural Sorority, Inc.
Description:
We are the Alpha Upsilon Colony/Kaleidoscope of Theta Nu Xi Multicultural Sorority, Inc. For more information about Alpha Upsilon specifically, please visit our instagram @fiu_thetanuxi. There you can find more details out AY and more up to date information about current and upcoming events. 

Theta Nu Xi Multicultural Sorority, Inc. was founded at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, by seven diverse women who sought to create an inclusive sisterhood. The Founders chose to transcend traditional boundaries with the creation of a new Greek letter organization that would embody the ideals of scholarship, service, sisterhood, leadership and multiculturalism. Despite being met with significant concerns about the viability of such an organization, the Founders held strong to their beliefs and pushed forward in creating the Sorority. Through their commitment and dedication, the dream of founding Theta Nu Xi came to fruition on April 11, 1997.

 

Our mission is to promote leadership, multiculturalism and self-improvement through academic excellence, involvement in and service to the campus and community, as well as being living examples of sisterhood across different races, cultures, religions, backgrounds and lifestyles.

 

Theta Nu Xi Fast Facts

Motto: Sisters of Diversity, Together as ONE!

Colors: Black, Lavender and Carolina Blue

Symbols: Tiger Swallowtail Butterfly & Sterling Silver Rose

National Philanthropy: Girl Up - A global movement of empowered young women leaders who defend gender equality.

Name: Thrift Club @ FIU
Description: N/A

Name: Turkish Student Association
Description: As a non-political organization, our mission is to promote various aspects of Turkish culture to FIU students and the broader community. It is our goal to introduce Turkish history, society, art, music, and sports to any member of FIU community who is interested in Turkish culture. Moreover, they will have the opportunity to meet other Turkish students at the university and engage in cultural exchange.

Name: Turning Point USA
Description: Turning Point USA educates students about the importance of fiscal responsibility, free markets, and limited government. Through non-partisan debate, dialogue, and discussion, Turning Point USA believes that every young person can be enlightened to true free market values. TPUSA activists strive to: - Educate students about the importance of fiscal responsibility, limited government, and free markets. With innovative messaging techniques and strategic outreach methods TPUSA is able to educate thousands of college students each day. - Identify student activists in every corner of the country who believe in limited government and individual liberty. TPUSA activists are the community organizers of the right. - Register students to vote. TPUSA has helped thousands of college students apply for voter registration and access vote-by-mail ballots. - Empower young activists to get involved in the fight for free markets and limited government. Through building strong campus networks, organizing conferences and training workshops, and equipping activists with the knowledge and strategies needed to combat the left, TPUSA empowers young people to make a difference within their own campus and community. - Organize young activists in chapters and networks on colleges across the country. TPUSA believes there is strength in organization, and our activists work tirelessly to build grassroots networks on every college campus in America. - Mobilize students who believe in free markets. TPUSA mobilizes its activist networks to get involved in activism, issue-advocacy, public policy education, and grassroots organization.

Name: Undergraduate Research Society
Description:
The purpose of the Undergraduate Research Society is to prepare undergraduates for graduate programs in biomedical, physical, and social sciences. The club will provide research opportunities, professional development, and mentorship to members to increase the competitiveness of their applications to fellowships, summer research programs, and graduate research programs.

Join us on WhatsApp! https://chat.whatsapp.com/LCU7I6OqT242h88VaIWOzi

Name: United Wesley
Description: Christian organization that meets for worship, small groups, fellowship, and service to help students cultivate community, nurture personal&spiritual growth, and change the world.

Name: University Apartments
Description:
University Apartments are courtyard-style, two-story apartment buildings. The apartments are for upper-class students.  It is home to 537 residents and 10 resident assistants.

Features

  • Full kitchen
  • Living room (2 and 4 bedroom apartments)
  • Local phone service
  • Laundry room on 1st floor of each building
  • Twin mattress (size 36 x 74 x 6)
  • Shared or private bathroom

Name: University Towers
Description:
University Towers is an apartment building housing mostly upper-class students. It is home to 481 residents and 10 resident assistants.

Features

  • Shared or private bathroom
  • Full kitchen
  • Living rooms (2 and 4 bedroom units)
  • Laundry room on 1st floor
  • Full mattress (size 54 x 80 x 6)

Name: Up Til Dawn
Description: We are an organization at Florida International University committed to raising money for St. Jude Children's Research Hospital by hosting an annual event whereby students, faculty, and alumni of Florida International University are encouraged to participate by forming teams of six and staying "Up 'til Dawn" to commemorate the parents that stay awake at the bedside of their children during treatment. Our inaugural event is expected to be held on November 15th, 2013 and our goal is to raise $50,000 so that St. Jude Children's Research Hospital can continue to accept patients regardless of race, nationality, religion, or their ability to pay.

Name: Veteran and Military Affairs
Description: Our office is committed to military-affiliated students having the support, resources, and community they need to achieve their academic, personal, and career goals. We strive to ensure each student has an exceptional experience before, during, and after their time at FIU.

Name: Volleyball - M
Description: Welcome to the FIU Men's Volleyball Club – where we bring the heat to the court! Whether you're an experienced player or just getting started, join our community of athletes for some high-energy volleyball action. Dive in and be part of the excitement!

Name: Volleyball - W
Description:
Please follow us on Instagram for further information about the club. If you have any questions shoot us a DM for faster responses. 

Thank you for taking interest in our team.

@fiuwvolleyballclub

Name: Water Environment Federation
Description: Official Student Chapter for the National Water Environment Federation and Florida Water Environment Association local section.

Name: Water Polo Club
Description: Here in this club, we strive to win a national collegiate club championship through the Collegiate Water Polo Associations (CWPA) Club league. Men's team competes in the Fall while women's team competes in the Spring. This club was founded in the Fall of 2020 and looks forward to competing and practicing for years to come. We practice at the Biscayne Bay Campus pool located at the gym on campus (Practice Times TBD for the Fall!). Please feel free to reach out to our primary contact or show up to practice for any further questions!

Name: We Are One
Description: We Are One hopes to foster individuals who yearn to help make a difference within the homeless community, incite awareness and activism to support more funding for the homeless community, increase cultural awareness and community building, develop altruistic students at the Florida International University, and to provide a welcoming community for all students of any background at Florida International University.

Name: Wellness and Recreation - BBC
Description:
From cardio to kayaks, the Wellness and Recreation Center on the beautiful Biscayne Bay Campus is home to a skilled staff, state-of-the-art gym equipment and outdoor running tracks, aquatic, tennis and basketball centers, which provide a wide variety of facilities that, inspire healthy lifestyles. Enrich your life through fitness and adventure activities or take on your friends in a battle for bragging rights through intramural sports. At the Wellness and Recreation Center - BBC, there is something for every interest and every fitness level. Explore all the ways we can help you stay fit, build friendships and have fun!

The Wellness and Recreation Center – BBC supports a holistic student lifestyle that supports all of our students toward their GRADUATION!

Name: Wellness and Recreation - MMC
Description: When you participate in extracurricular activities like those offered through the Wellness & Recreation Center, you find opportunities for leadership, social and multicultural interaction, camaraderie, physical activity and stress reduction that you can’t find in the classroom. Refuse to lose – there’s something for everyone; we're more than just a gym!

Name: Wolfe University Center
Description: The Wolfe Center enriches the University and community by providing support and access for experiential learning, dynamic growth, and meaningful experiences. We are home to cultural, educational, and recreational programs whether they occur in our recently renovated multi-purpose ballrooms, our newly opened student video game lounge, our world class exercise and aquatics facility, or our performing arts center, the Mary Anne Wolfe Theater. Stop by and find out why so many think of the Wolfe University Center as home.

Name: Wolfsonian Public Humanities Lab
Description: The Wolfsonian Public Humanities Lab (WPHL) serves as FIU’s hub for public-facing humanities research, teaching and engagement. Our lab uses FIU’s status as an urban research institution and its strategic location in Miami to capture and magnify the creative, scholarly and pedagogical expertise of faculty, staff and students who are committed to doing public-facing work.

Name: Women in Computer Science
Description:
We are a community of women whose mission is to help individuals find their passion within technology.

Our goals are to promote and support the community of women in computer science and technology at FIU.

We offer programs and events that encourage you to discover new opportunities, learn how to overcome challenges, and build lasting friendships.

Name: Women in CyberSecurity
Description: At WiCyS, a global community of women, allies and advocates, we are dedicated to bringing talented women together to celebrate and foster their passion and drive for cybersecurity. We unite local communities of aspiring and thriving women cybersecurity professionals across the world to collaborate, share their knowledge, network and mentor. We create opportunities through professional development programs, conferences, career fairs, and more.

Name: Women in Medicine
Description:
Women in Medicine (WIM) was established as a secure hub for young college women on a pre-health track, providing a sisterhood where members can bond and share knowledge. The organization offers various opportunities such as lectures, volunteering, skill-learning events, and more to prepare these women for their future healthcare professions. WIM's mission is to empower young college women and equip them with the necessary tools to succeed in their healthcare journeys.

Interested individuals can join through the Linktree platform, which provides access to the organization's Instagram channel where daily opportunities and news are shared. WIM aims to create a supportive community, foster knowledge exchange, and empower its members as they pursue their dreams of becoming healthcare professionals.

Name: Women Inspired to Serve and Educate
Description:
Women Inspired to Serve and Educate (W.I.S.E.) endeavors to be a positive source of empowerment that will aid all women within Florida International University (FIU) and our greater community. W.I.S.E. encourages genuine and sustainable progress regarding the general state of women. We aim to create and support educational initiatives that encourage the timely completion of a higher education, particularly for subgroups within this population that have been historically marginalized.  Our mission also aims to assist in fostering socioeconomic gains for women and lead effective research development regarding issues currently impacting us within our society. Women Inspired to Serve and Educate seeks to promote diversity, philanthropy, spirituality, in addition to positive self-image and individuality within the hearts and minds of women within FIU and abroad.

W.I.S.E aims to wholistcally support women.  Join in and serve within our various sectors:
-Women’s Health, Wellness & Self-Image

-Political Advocacy

-Culture & Diversity

-Professional Development, Leadership & Mentorship

-Spirituality  

-Research Development

-Education

-Financial Wellness

-Philanthropy &Community Activism

-Artistic Creativity & Innovation

-The WISE Initiative (Bi-Monthly newsletter for women of FIU)

Name: Women's Center
Description: We provide women with programs and services related to their intellectual, professional, social, and emotional growth. We educate and advocate for systemic changes that will improve the lives of women and men.

Name: Women's Transportation Seminar
Description: Welcome to the Women's Transportation Seminar page. The Women’s Transportation Seminar (WTS) Student Chapter at the Florida International University (FIU) was founded in August 2013. Our Chapter is dedicated to let more students and professionals recognize the FIU WTS Student Chapter and help students, especially female students, with their careers in the area of Transportation Engineering.

Name: Zeta Beta Tau
Description:
The mission of Zeta Beta Tau Fraternity (ZBT) is to foster and develop in its brotherhood the tenets of its Credo: Intellectual Awareness, Social Responsibility, Integrity and Brotherly Love, in order to prepare its brothers for positions of leadership and service within their communities.

Mindful of its founding in 1898 as the world’s first Jewish Fraternity, ZBT will preserve and cultivate its relationships within the Jewish community. Since 1954, ZBT has been committed to its policy of non-sectarian brotherhood, and values the diversity of its brothers. ZBT will recruit and initiate men of good character, regardless of religion, race or creed who are accepting of these principles.
